as <$50 000 and <$150 000 per QALY gained, respectively.
RESULTS: At 10 years, the intervention was projected to cost an
average of $2356 (95% uncertainty interval, -$264 to $4611)
more per participant than the control arm and gain 0.06 (95%
uncertainty interval, 0.01-0.10) QALYs. The LABBPS intervention
was highly cost-effective, with a mean cost of $42 717 per QALY
gained (58% probability of being highly and 96% of being at
least intermediately cost-effective). Exclusive use of generic
drugs improved the cost-effectiveness to $17 162 per QALY
gained. The LABBPS intervention would be only intermediately
cost-effective if pharmacists were less likely to intensify
antihypertensive medications when systolic blood pressure was
